The paper evaluates eight parallel graph processing systems, which suggests that it could belong to the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) sub-category. The datasets used in the evaluation include Twitter and ClueWeb, which are commonly used in the field of Information Retrieval (cs.IR), but the focus of the paper is on the performance and scalability of the graph processing systems rather than on information retrieval. The paper also discusses system tuning heuristics, which could suggest that it belongs to the Database (cs.DB) or Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-categories. Finally, the paper evaluates the usability of the systems, which could suggest that it belongs to the Human-Computer Interaction (cs.HC) sub-category, but this is less likely given the focus on performance and scalability. Overall, the most likely sub-categories are cs.DC, cs.DB, cs.DS, cs.CE (Computational Engineering, Finance, and Science), and cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture).
